          "title": "Verify Keystone reflects Admin list-view changes with accessible list behavior",
          "description": "Verify Keystone reflects Admin list-view changes with accessible list behavior\n\nTest Steps:\n\n1. Log in to https://ops.acchindra.com/admin using username/email \"adminacc\" and password \"adminacc@2026\", then confirm the admin list-view change under test is present in the reachable admin context.\n   Expected: The admin-side list-view change is visible or otherwise confirmable in Admin; if the admin surface is not visible, mark the test blocked.\n\n2. Navigate to https://ops.acchindra.com/shockwave and, when prompted, log in using username/email \"adminacc\" and password \"adminacc@2026\".\n   Expected: Keystone authentication succeeds and the page remains at https://ops.acchindra.com/shockwave/.\n\n3. Navigate to the Keystone object/list context that corresponds to the admin list-view change under test.\n   Expected: The corresponding Keystone list context opens; if no navigation or list context is visible, record the same blocked condition observed during inspection.\n\n4. Verify the visible table/list/grid container, headers, rows or empty-state, and absence of loading/error state.\n   Expected: The Keystone list view renders a stable data view or empty-state without indefinite loading or errors.\n\n5. Verify the admin-side list-view change is reflected in Keystone, such as the expected list-view selection, columns, sorting/filtering behavior, or visibility change defined by the admin configuration.\n   Expected: Keystone matches the admin list-view configuration. If the expected change is absent after reload, capture evidence and report propagation failure.\n\n6. Perform accessibility checks on the visible list-view area: confirm keyboard focus can reach the list controls and rows, visible focus indication is present, controls have accessible names, and the list/table/grid exposes meaningful headers or labels to assistive technology.\n   Expected: The list view is keyboard operable and screen-reader understandable. Any missing accessible names, focus traps, or unlabeled table/grid structure are reported as @a11y defects.\n\nTest Steps:\n\n1. Log in to https://ops.acchindra.com/admin using username/email \"adminacc\" and password \"adminacc@2026\", then confirm the admin list-view change under test is present in the reachable admin context.\n   Expected: The admin-side list-view change is visible or otherwise confirmable in Admin; if the admin surface is not visible, mark the test blocked.\n\n2. Navigate to https://ops.acchindra.com/shockwave and, when prompted, log in using username/email \"adminacc\" and password \"adminacc@2026\".\n   Expected: Keystone authentication succeeds and the page remains at https://ops.acchindra.com/shockwave/.\n\n3. Navigate to the Keystone object/list context that corresponds to the admin list-view change under test.\n   Expected: The corresponding Keystone list context opens; if no navigation or list context is visible, record the same blocked condition observed during inspection.\n\n4. Verify the visible table/list/grid container, headers, rows or empty-state, and absence of loading/error state.\n   Expected: The Keystone list view renders a stable data view or empty-state without indefinite loading or errors.\n\n5. Verify the admin-side list-view change is reflected in Keystone, such as the expected list-view selection, columns, sorting/filtering behavior, or visibility change defined by the admin configuration.\n   Expected: Keystone matches the admin list-view configuration. If the expected change is absent after reload, capture evidence and report propagation failure.\n\n6. Perform accessibility checks on the visible list-view area: confirm keyboard focus can reach the list controls and rows, visible focus indication is present, controls have accessible names, and the list/table/grid exposes meaningful headers or labels to assistive technology.\n   Expected: The list view is keyboard operable and screen-reader understandable. Any missing accessible names, focus traps, or unlabeled table/grid structure are reported as @a11y defects.",
